<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF8CFFF0FE3F19598629B164" authority="(Stal, 1859)" baseAuthorityName="Stal" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[422,893,852,879]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Limnogonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="826" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="franciscanus">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF8CFFF0FE3F195987B8B164" bold="true" box="[422,748,852,879]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="826">Limnogonus franciscanus</emphasis>
(St√•l, 1859)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E8403669FF8CFFF0FF59198785ACB626" blockId="27.[160,1155,906,1069]" pageId="27" pageNumber="826">
This gerrid water strider was common and abundant. This species is well known from St. Thomas, 
<collectingRegion id="2A3BF88BFF8CFFF0FEB119A184D4B1CE" box="[296,384,940,965]" country="United States Virgin Islands" name="Saint John" pageId="27" pageNumber="826">St. John</collectingRegion>
and St. Croix (
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF8CFFF0FDBB19A187FFB1CE" author="Barber HG" box="[546,683,940,965]" pageId="27" pageNumber="826" pagination="264 - 441" refId="ref22283" refString="Barber HG. 1939. Insects of Porto Rico and the Virgin Islands: Hemiptera-Heteroptera (excepting the Miridae and Corixidae). Sci Surv Porto Rico Virgin Islands. 14: 264 - 441." type="journal article" year="1939">Barber 1939</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF8CFFF0FD2119A18165B1CE" author="de Kort-Gommer M &amp; Nieser N" box="[696,1073,940,965]" pageId="27" pageNumber="826" pagination="72 - 87" refId="ref24300" refString="de Kort-Gommer M, Nieser N. 1969. Records of Antillean water striders (Heteroptera). Stud Fauna Curacao Carib Isl. 30: 72 - 87." type="journal article" year="1969">de Kort-Gommer and Nieser 1969</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF8CFFF0FBA419A185B0B1E3" author="Nieser N" pageId="27" pageNumber="826" pagination="94 - 138" refId="ref27928" refString="Nieser N. 1970 a. Gerridae of Suriname and the Amazon with additional records of other Neotropical species (Hemiptera - Heteroptera). Stud Fauna Suriname Other Guyanas. 47 (1): 94 - 138." type="journal article" year="1970">Nieser 1970a</bibRefCitation>
). We found this species on St. Thomas in ghuts, ponds, and mangrove brackish pools; wherever there was quiet, relatively calm water with little to no obvious surface current.
</paragraph>
